description.text:
Der Spoolholder ist speziell nur für den Anet A6 Drucker entworfen.

Montiert wird der Halter indem man ihn zwischen Display und Frame von oben steckt als Ersatz von den Distanzhülsen und einfach mit den Originalschrauben wieder verschraubt.

Gegenüber der Vorgängerversion gibt es einen extra aufschiebbaren Bügel als Führung vom Filament und um zu verhindern, dass das Filament neben die Spule springen kann. Der Bügel kann waagerecht für normale Teile montiert werden und für besonders hohe Teile kann der Bügel senkrecht aufgeschoben werden. Es empfiehlt sich einen Filzstreifen am Bügel aufzukleben, der als leichte Bremse funktioniert. so kann die Spule sich nicht aufgrund von einer möglichen Unwucht selber abrollen.

Der Spoolholder ist gedacht, um die Spule zentrisch aufzunehmen. Dazu benötigt es noch eine Zentrierachse für die unterschiedlichen Spulengrössen. Dies ist wichtig, denn sonst funktioniert der Bügel nicht richtig. Ausserdem können grössere Spulen nur mit Zentrierung aufgenommen werden, da sie sonst drohen auf dem Frame zu schleifen.

Eine Zentrierte Aufnahme der Spule ist ausserdem für einen qualitativ hohen Druck sehr wichtig. Wenn die Spule nicht zentriert wird, so muss der Druckkopf zuweilen recht stark an der Spule zotteln, was zu Layerverschiebungen und anderen Effekten führen kann.

Die Zentrierachse für die Spulenaufnahme ist optional und nur empfehlenswert zum Druck, wenn der Drucker bereits sehr gut kalibriert ist. Versätze oder zu ungenauer Druck kann dazu führen, dass die Zentrierstücke sich nicht leicht auf die Achse schrauben lassen. Ausserdem benötigt man noch 2 8mm 6mm 19mm Industrie-Kugellager.

Es gibt aber bei Thingiverse einige andere gute Beispiele für das Zentrieren von den Spulen.

title: Fan Mount for Kossel Mini Delta Printer

description.text:
This is a custom fan mount for:

  • hot end cooling: 1 axial fan with 40mmx400mm
  • printed part cooling for extreme overhangs: 3x 50x15mm radial blower fans
  • holding DC42 IR z-Probe

Everything can be printed without supports.
Just make sure that you print the fan shrouds on the tip.

You´ll need some m3 screws and nuts. i also recommend to add some spacers.
You need to tighten the screws and nuts quite strong: the blower should not rotate downwards. In a next revision i´ll add some mechanism to prevent the blower from falling down (happend only once until now).
I also added some brass threaded inserts after some weeks of printing, but i don´t think this absolutely necessary.

Some minor notes:

  • One blower cools the IR, which seems to be no problem.
  • There is enough room for silicone sock around the heater block
  • nozzle ends quite high above the printed parts
  • this is design iteration no. 4 (1-3 have never been released, currently working on 5)
  • this is my first upload :-)
  • step files are attached for further customization, but please do any changes as a remix
  • feedback is always welcome

See it live:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NfBKPdQI14Q

January 2018: Still my favourite design. Altough i´m thinking about reducing the number of blowers to 2 or 1 and distributing airflow via a better fan duct.

title: Lionel Flat Car Track Cleaner Addon

description.text:
Track cleaning cars are expensive for O Gauge. I've seen some for well over $100 and I just don't want to pay that much. I had a beat up Lionel 6-17407 Flatcar that I have been using for a while with a wadded up scotch bright pad screwed into the bottom. I decided it was time to make this more professional looking.

Parts needed:

  1. A cheap flat car or box car to modify with the cleaning pickups
  2. Two m2.5x10 screws. I bought a lot of them a while back here: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01N8XJVHQ/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o08_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1)
  3. One round 8-32 inch x 1-1/2 inch machine screw with nut. I get these cheaper at home depot but something like this:
    https://www.amazon.com/Hillman-Group-7668-Machine-8-32-Inch/dp/B000BQW6AA/ref=sr_1_9?s=hi&ie=UTF8&qid=1487882293&sr=1-9&keywords=8+32+round
  4. Package of scotch bright pads. I get them cheaper locally but here is an example:
    https://www.amazon.com/Scotch-Brite-Heavy-Industrial-Scouring/dp/B003FYJ83S/ref=sr_1_cc_1_a_it

To install:

  1. Print the parts as oriented in the file
  2. Push the 8-32 screw through the bottom part with the large indention so it sits flush. You may need to drill it out some so the screw slides right through. I had to drill one part but not the other.
  3. Push the top down onto the screw. There are indention's for button head m2.5 screws so they sit flush.
  4. Cut a scotch bright pad to fit. I get 2 cleaners out of 1 pad. It's designed to only require one cut of the pad.
  5. Place the pad inside the opening like you would sand paper in a block and then tighten down the two m2.5 screws till they hold the pad.
  6. Drill an 8-32 hole into the bottom of the car you will be using as your cleaning car and slide the whole thing in and tighten down the nut

Depending on the car height you can add a spacer so that the scrubber is always touching the track. Load up the car with something heavy so that the wheels stay on the track. Ideally the scrubber is compressed some.

In my example I printed 2 of these and stuck them right behind the wheels so I don't take out scenery material as it goes around the track.

It's working really well. I'll add a video once I have fully completed the car.

I have added a container that can be printed for a flatbed that can hide the screws and also hold extra weight. I did not create the container from scratch. It is based off of

http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:38392

but heavily modified. It's been resized and scaled up to O Scale size to best fit 2 of these in the flatcar. I have also modified it with a removable top that has a lip so that it locks into the top without glue. This also makes it easier to print with less support needed. I can then glue these open shipping box bottoms to the flat car and still get to the screws so I can change the pads by removing the top. Whole goal is to hide the components so the flatcar looks like any other car on the track.

XYZ Printing Davinci Mini

I recommend thicker than normal walls since you will be using screws with this.

You must print the container with supports. They are very easy to remove after printing as it's been oriented to print with minimal support. If you tend to get a lot of pull up on edges on your printer a brim on the container might also be a good idea

description.text:
EDIT 02-25-2015
I'm using a very light 1-layer 5% infill raft to get my supports to stick to my bed just for the "Hilt & Pt of Blade" print. I'm on a glass bed, so sticking was getting a little tricky for the thin supports.

.

EDIT 02-24-2017
Fixed Pegs
Pegs Need a Raft & print laying flat

I used the whole sword stl (found here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1383445) and cut it into 4 pieces (at most 235mm). Since my printer supports 240mm, I made them 235mm high. Don't let the software scale the pegs. They are in fact that small. The holes aren't big since the blade is thin.

So, they're basically the same as the one I remixed it from except that I added pegs and holes for the pegs. This is going to be a work in progress until I can get the peg sizes right. But the one that says it's the actual size of the hole is what I used to make the holes. I made the pegs 0.10mm smaller than the hole. Hopefully that works. You'll need 14 pegs total if you use all of your holes. You don't necessarily need to, but it may help, especially when you want to make sure you have it turned the right way.

This is my first Remix that I'm putting on here, only because someone asked for it. So thanks to the original poster for putting this up there.

The pegs are only for alignment so you can glue it in place.
Good luck, and if this works, don't forget to thank the original OP, and post images!!!

I'm using 20% infill to start.
Both of the Hilt parts NEED supports.
I didn't need any for the blade parts though.

One thing to learn from this is to look at the supports your slicer gives you. If it looks unfeasible, it is. I found a way to add more supports in Simplify3D. I added the gcode for this part and a separate support file. If your slicer can import supports, do that so you can have a look at the file before you send it to print. So while I like my big-ass living room TV, one of the concessions made is that the speakers are mounted forwarding downward. Speakers were definitely an after-thought as it was assumed one would use a receiver. We definitely do, but for times when I'm not watching something that requires amazing audio, I wanted to save power (and avoid throwing extra heat in the house on hot summer days) by using the TV speakers.

Well since the speakers are facing our entertainment stand instead of facing outwards, the audio is tinny, muffled, and requires turning the TV up louder than one should have to.

So I built a simple stand to try to better reflect the audio forward. It's not scientific. It can be improved (e.g. I need to make a top for it, or make the outlet more of a horn design) but, functionally, it works as a good first pass.

The dimensions are for my Vizio 65" which has a speaker grille that is around 38x108 mm with a stand that's around 63mm in height.

The base requires an M5-.8 hex nut. The knob is built for a M5-.8 hex bolt, 50mm in length. I found both of these at my local OSH hardware store. The screw and nut were chosen to be compatible with GoPro's hardware. As a result, you can elect not to print the "Knob" and just use a GoPro knob that you likely already have.
The Frame is printed with 2 shells, 20% infill, a 0.2mm layer height. Supports must be used. You will need to clean up the part with an Xacto knife to remove the supports from the cutouts in the frame.
The Base is printed with 2 shells, 20% infill, a 0.2mm layer height. Supports are recommended when printing (only used to help with the screw hole). Removing the supports from the hole is easily done with an Xacto.
The Knob is printed with 2 shells, 20% infill, a 0.2mm layer height. Supports are not needed.
Note: The units of the STL files are in inches.

description.text:
Work in progress!

This is a 2 switch box that mounts on top of the tower using the existing screws or similarly sized M3 hardware. I used it to hook up switches to my LEDs and part fan so that I could disable them as needed without having to disconnect JST connectors or something similar.

The switches I made it for are "SPST Mini" toggle switches that I got at Radio Shack. There's a slot for the little guide washer so they stay straight. To fit them in the box I had to remove the bottom-most nut on the switch assembly, the one intended to be secured inside the box. I set it up so that I could wire up and secure the switches with the backplate removed, then tuck the wires in through the slot at the side until they were in the dome cutout, then slide the backplate on to secure it all.

The holes at the top line up with the tower screws so you can use a small screwdriver or allen wrench to secure it. I used M3 screws and an allen wrench. My screw holes didn't line up perfectly and I think I drilled one out a little bit to make it fit nicely. I don't remember if I fixed this STL yet. Edit: I printed the bottom layer by itself and the holes matched up with my screws, so I must have fixed it. But let me know if anyone has any trouble with it.

The back plate was a little tight too, I had to file it down some to get it on.

I didn't like how the screw access holes in the top just sat open like that so I made a little bulb and fan icon to stick in them. In my picture I colored the upper ridges with a sharpie, but you could also do a filament switch to achieve the same thing.

Will upload new versions as I fix the little things wrong that I mentioned above.

title: Silicone insulation sock for Raise3D V2 hotend

description.text:
Introduction

This is a reusable mold designed for two-part RTV silicone casting compounds and putties. The mold creates a silicone sock which covers the heat block to insulate it. There are two separate files for both the left and right extruder hotends. I have not actually explored the thermal performance of this insulating method compared to other solutions, though, so I can't guarantee that it is better, but it sure looks cooler!

This is version 1 of this, so please feel free to submit makes and feedback. I made the model in OnShape, a nice online CAD package. You can view it there and even export it if you have an OnShape account (it's free). I also uploaded Solidworks part files for it, if you want another format, let me know. These files also include parts and an assembly for the hotend itself.

Edit version 1.1:
Created an air gap between the silicone sock and the heat block. Previously, the silicone was 2mm thick, now it is 1mm thick with standoffs which create a 1mm air gap. The sock is slightly more difficult to release from the mold, but it should insulate well. Filleted the bottom of the sock.

OnShape link V1.0: https://cad.onshape.com/documents/755775ac5ac5e8ceb9784b7d/w/7a709f9d2c30f75e0e5a75b8/e/5cf270a76a18d9ef2997f353

OnShape link V1.1:
https://cad.onshape.com/documents/755775ac5ac5e8ceb9784b7d/w/8876288e3425e86ff16e77c3/e/19da563b0818a4e38b896471

Versions/Future plans:
V1.0: Initial release
--> V1.1: Create an air gap between the silicone and heat block for better insulation.
V1.2: Improve the mold design to make extraction easier.

Instructions

  1. Print the mold. Any rigid material is fine, but print it fairly sturdy. 3 shells and 25-50% infill recommended. If you're using pourable silicone, maybe a flexible filament would work, I haven't tried it.
  2. Get some silicone. Look for high temperature RTV silicone casting compound or putty. I have tried two types: TAP Plastics platinum cure (translucent white, 260°C), and Castaldo Quick-Sil putty (green, 315°C). The TAP Plastics stuff works well, but it's a bit expensive. The Quick-Sil putty is available through McMaster and Amazon, can be gotten in small (and cheap) quantities, cures super fast, and is rated for higher temperatures. However, it is infused with mineral oil, which will smoke a bit when heated until it burns out. I didn't use any release agent on either of these, but it probably would have made extraction easier, so feel free to try it.
  3. Make sure the two mold parts fit together easily. If the little pillar on the top part melted a bit during printing or something, just file/sand it until it fits loosely, it's only there to index the pieces when mating. The top piece should slide down far enough that the pillar is flush with the small hole on the bottom of the bottom piece. The rounds on the ends of the top piece should be touching the walls of the bottom piece.
  4. Prepare your silicone. You'll need about 15 grams of it. Follow the instructions. If using the Castaldo Quick-Sil putty, you must move quickly once you start mixing!
  5. Pour the silicone. It is meant to fill the mold until the silicone is flush with the top of the mold, or slightly lower. For low viscosity stuff like the TAP Platinum, you can just put both mold pieces together and slowly pour the silicone in. For high viscosity or putty, you'll have to pour/pack some in the bottom (and walls for putty), then squish the second part in, then fill it until it's flush with the top of the mold. For the putty, I used a small arbor press to push the mold together, but probably any hard surface will do if you put your weight into it.
  6. Wait. Let the silicone cure for the full curing time. I heated my printer's build plate to 50C and set the mold on top of it to help it cure.
  7. Extract the silicone. I used the back side of a hobby knife to run along the edges of the mold to pull the silicone off the walls. Then, I used some vise-grips and pliers to pry the two sections apart (see photo). If you used release agent, you'll probably have an easier time.
  8. Clean up the silicone. Some very minor cleanup might be needed. Most importantly would be the hole for the nozzle, you'll probably have a small ring of flashing that needs to be removed. Tweezers work well. Also, if your silicone was taller than the top of the mold, you'll have to shave the top down, as it won't fit under the heatsink. If you used the Castaldo putty, you might want to wait a day or two for it to "sweat" out its mineral oil, otherwise it will smoke when heated until it's gone. Not harmful, but a bit annoying.
  9. Put it on your hotend! The silicone sock splits in the back and top, so you will be able to slide it over the heater block without removing anything, although removing the side cooling fan will make it easier. You're done.

For this mystery project, I wanted to research an unpopular president that has made some significant contribution to society, but is rarely recognized. This president certainly fits this criteria due to his quiet demeanor and unrecognized achievements.
Mystery Artifact Created By: Diego Espinoza

Read the Clues to Determine Which President this Artifact Represents

Clues

  • This object was a gift to the president.
  • This gift symbolizes a sense of gratitude towards the president.
  • This gift was worn by the president.
  • This gift was given to the president after he signed a legislation.

Can you tell...

  • Which president is represented here?
  • Which group of people gave the gift to the president?
  • What legislation did the president sign that made him so popular among the group of people?

Object: Native American (Sioux Tribe) Feathered Headdress

President: Calvin Coolidge

Details:
During his presidency, Calvin Coolidge signed the Indian Citizenship Act in 1924. To show a sense of gratitude and commence a new relationship between the government and Native Americans, the Sioux tribe adopted President Coolidge and gave him a feather headdress as a sign of a "united welcome".

Throughout his presidency, Coolidge was a strong advocate for tribal cultural rights. He had great sympathy for the the Native American community because of their harsh treatment and poor conditions in which they had to live during the years of persecution and forced assimilation (during the Jackson presidency). President Coolidge met with several tribal leaders to further strengthen relations after the signing of the Native American Citizenship Act. In addition, he accepted tribal membership from the Sioux tribe.

Contribution:
This act gave Native Americans voting rights and granted them citizenship. The act came in response to the Native Americans' involvement in the military. During World War I, 10,000 Native Americans participated in the war, even though they were not considered American citizens. President Coolidge signed the act not only to grant citizenship but also to give Native Americans the chance to integrate into the American lifestyle. In result, some of the Native Americans became farmers.

Impact on America:
After a long history of disenfranchisement with the Native American community, Native Americans were finally considered Americans after President Coolidge signed the act. They were given rights and citizenship which led to several job opportunities.
